<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: ORANGE; POLICE TO CONDUCT SOBRIETY CHECKS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By LESLEY WRIGHT 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Drivers should be prepared to run into a sobriety checkpoint somewhere in the 
city beginning at 9 tonight. 
</P>
<P>
 Police, who are not disclosing the location, warn that some traffic may be 
delayed while drivers are checked for signs of drinking. 
</P>
<P>
 Officers randomly stop about every 10th car, according to Sheryn Mauerhan of 
the department's traffic bureau. Those who fail the field sobriety test, which 
primarily tests balance and coherence, will be arrested. 
</P>
<P>
 The checkpoint program, funded by a grant from the California Office of 
Traffic Safety, conducts these random checks on a monthly basis. LESLEY WRIGHT 
</P>
</TEXT>
