<HEADLINE>
<P>
TODAY'S GAMES AT A GLANCE; WORLD CUP USA '94 / THE FIRST ROUND; TODAY'S GAMES 
AT A GLANCE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CHRIS DUFRESNE 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 GROUP B at Silverdome, Pontiac, Mich. 
</P>
<P>
 Sweden vs. Russia 
</P>
<P>
 * TIME: 4:30 p.m. PDT. 
</P>
<P>
 * TV: ESPN, Univision, KSCI (Russian). 
</P>
<P>
 * KEY MATCHUPS: Both teams play a tough, European style, clogging the midfield 
and waiting patiently for opportunities.At least that was the scouting report. 
Inexplicably, Russia changed its style in a 2-0 drubbing by Brazil, switching 
to more man-to-man coverage. Swedish Coach Tommy Svensson said he would welcome 
a similar Russian strategy against his team. 
</P>
<P>
 Sweden is a team of few stars, forward Martin Dahlin being the exception, and 
prefers to operate in group attacks. Russia, because of mass player defections, 
has lost considerable striking power. Forward Sergei Yuran is its best 
offensive weapon. In many ways, the teams are similar. "There will be a big 
battle in the midfield, that's for sure," said Anders Limpar, a Swedish 
midfielder. 
</P>
<P>
 * OUTLOOK: Having not yet played Brazil in the group, Sweden is in no position 
to blow this game. Henrik Larsson, who set up the tying goal against Cameroon, 
did not practice Thursday because of a sore knee but is expected to be ready 
today. 
</P>
<P>
 * OUTCOME: This game should be played close to the vest, unless the Russians 
figure they have nothing to lose and unveil another attacking scheme. Sweden 
squeezes out a close one, 2-1, and Russia packs. CHRIS DUFRESNE 
</P>
</TEXT>
